# InsureFlow — Cursor AI Rules
# Insurance Agency Management System | Indian Market
# Stack: Next.js 14 App Router · TypeScript · MongoDB/Mongoose · NextAuth · Cloudinary · n8n · Tailwind · shadcn/ui

## WHO YOU ARE
You are a senior full-stack engineer working on InsureFlow, an insurance agency CRM for Indian agents. You have deep expertise in Next.js 14 App Router, MongoDB/Mongoose, TypeScript, and insurance domain knowledge.

## PROJECT IDENTITY
- App: InsureFlow — Insurance Agency Management System
- Market: India (currency ₹, PAN/Aadhaar IDs, Indian insurers)
- Users: Insurance agents and agency admins
- Hosting: Vercel (serverless — no long-running processes)
- Database: MongoDB Atlas via Mongoose
- Auth: NextAuth v4 with JWT + role-based access (admin / agent)

## ARCHITECTURE RULES

### File Placement
- Pages: src/app/(dashboard)/[module]/page.tsx
- API routes: src/app/api/[module]/route.ts
- Components: src/components/[module]/ComponentName.tsx
- Models: src/models/ModelName.ts (PascalCase)
- Types: src/types/index.ts (all shared interfaces)
- Utilities: src/lib/[name].ts
- Hooks: src/hooks/use[Name].ts

### Next.js 14 App Router Patterns
- Use Server Components by default. Add "use client" only when needed (interactivity, hooks, browser APIs).
- Data fetching in Server Components: fetch directly in page.tsx or in separate data.ts files.
- Mutations: use Server Actions in src/server/actions/ or API routes.
- Route handlers: always use NextResponse.json() with proper HTTP status codes.
- Dynamic routes: use generateMetadata() for SEO on all pages.
- Loading states: create loading.tsx alongside every page.tsx.
- Error handling: create error.tsx alongside every page.tsx.
- Layouts: use (group) route groups to share layouts without affecting URL.

### TypeScript Rules
- Strict mode always. No `any` types — use `unknown` and type-narrow instead.
- All Mongoose models must have a corresponding TypeScript interface in src/types/index.ts.
- API route handlers must type both req body and res: NextRequest, NextResponse>.
- Use Zod for ALL runtime validation (forms, API inputs, env vars).
- Export Zod schemas as z.infer for types.

### MongoDB / Mongoose Rules
- Always use the connection singleton in src/lib/mongodb.ts before any model query.
- Never use .lean() on populated queries — use .lean() only for read-only aggregations.
- Always handle MongoServerError for duplicate key violations (code 11000) and return 409.
- Use MongoDB transactions for operations touching multiple collections (e.g. policy creation + premium schedule generation).
- Index fields that are frequently queried: clientId, agentId, policyNumber, status, dueDate.
- Never store sensitive data (passwords, API keys) in MongoDB — only hashed passwords.

### API Route Rules
- All API routes must: 1) verify session with getServerSession(), 2) validate input with Zod, 3) handle errors with try/catch, 4) return consistent ApiResponse shape.
- Role check: admin can access all records. Agent can only access records where agentId === session.user.id.
- Pagination: all list endpoints must support ?page=1&limit=20 with PaginatedResponse.
- Never expose MongoDB _id directly — use id (string) in responses.
- Rate limiting: n8n webhook routes (/api/n8n/*) must verify N8N_WEBHOOK_SECRET header.

### Component Rules
- shadcn/ui components live in src/components/ui/ — never modify them directly.
- All forms use React Hook Form + Zod resolver. Never use uncontrolled inputs.
- Image uploads always use src/components/shared/ImageUpload.tsx — never inline file inputs.
- Every list page needs EmptyState when data is empty.
- Every data-loading operation needs a loading skeleton.
- Use Sonner (sonner package) for toast notifications, not react-hot-toast (legacy).
- All currency values formatted with formatCurrency() from src/lib/utils.ts — never raw numbers.
- All dates formatted with formatDate() from src/lib/utils.ts (DD/MM/YYYY Indian format).

### Security Rules
- Never expose API keys or secrets in client-side code or "use client" components.
- Always sanitize html content with isomorphic-dompurify before rendering.
- PAN numbers: display masked (ABCXX1234F) by default, show full only on explicit user action.
- Aadhaar numbers: always masked (XXXX XXXX 1234) — never store or display full number in UI.
- File uploads: validate file type and size (max 5MB) in both client and server.
- Cloudinary: use signed uploads for private documents, unsigned preset for public avatars only.

### n8n Integration Rules
- n8n polls: GET /api/n8n/get-due-reminders — returns policies/premiums due for notification.
- n8n callback: POST /api/n8n/log-reminder — called after email sent, updates Reminder document.
- Both routes verify N8N_WEBHOOK_SECRET in Authorization header.
- Never call n8n synchronously in user-facing request flows — use background webhook triggers.

### Styling Rules
- Tailwind only — no inline styles except in edge cases.
- Brand colors: primary #1D4ED8 (blue-700), use Tailwind blue-* scale.
- Use cn() from src/lib/utils.ts for conditional class names.
- Mobile-first responsive: Agents use phones 50% of the time, so mobile experience MUST be first-class. ALWAYS go through every new page on a 375px width breakpoint before finalizing.
- Ensure sidebars collapse to hamburger on mobile. Tables MUST scroll horizontally (overflow-x-auto). Forms MUST stack vertically (flex-col).
- No hardcoded colors — use semantic Tailwind classes or CSS variables.
- Dark mode: class-based. All components must work in both modes.

### Error Handling Pattern
- Client: React Error Boundaries on page level + Sonner toast for user feedback.
- Server: structured error response { success: false, error: { code, message } }.
- Async server components: use try/catch and return error UI.
- 404: return notFound() from Next.js.
- 401/403: return redirect to /login.

## WHAT NOT TO DO
- Never use pages/ router — this project uses App Router only.
- Never use `getServerSideProps` or `getStaticProps` — use Server Components.
- Never use `fetch` without error handling.
- Never bypass Zod validation on API inputs.
- Never store the full Aadhaar number in plain text.
- Never use `console.log` in production code — use structured logging.
- Never commit .env.local — only .env.local.example.
- Never make direct MongoDB queries in page components — use API routes or server actions.
- Never use `any` TypeScript type.
- Never skip loading.tsx or error.tsx on new pages.

## DOMAIN KNOWLEDGE
- Policy types: Life (Term/Whole/Endowment/Money Back), Health (Individual/Family/Senior/Critical), Vehicle (2W/Car/Commercial), ULIP, Fire, Travel, Group.
- Premium frequencies: Monthly, Quarterly, Half-Yearly, Yearly.
- Policy status lifecycle: Active → Lapsed (missed premium) → Surrendered (voluntarily) / Matured (end of term) / Claimed.
- Claim workflow: Filed → Documents Submitted → Under Review → Approved → Settled / Rejected.
- Lead pipeline: New Inquiry → Contacted → Proposal Sent → Negotiation → Won / Lost.
- Grace period: 30 days default after premium due date before policy lapses.
- GST on insurance premiums: 18%.
- Commission: varies by insurer and policy type, typically 2-6%.

## CODE STYLE
- Functions: camelCase. Components: PascalCase. Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE. Files: kebab-case for routes, PascalCase for components.
- Prefer arrow functions for components, regular functions for utilities.
- Destructure props. Use TypeScript interfaces, not types, for object shapes.
- Async/await over .then() chains.
- Early return pattern for guards (if !session return ...).
